Inheritance is an OOP mechanism where one class acquires the properties (variables) and behaviors (methods) of another class.
Implemented using the keyword: extends
â–º Parent class â†’ Superclass
â–º Child class â†’ Subclass
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
âºï¸ Types of Inheritance (Conceptually)
â˜ There are 5 main types of inheritance in Object-Oriented Programming:
âŠ Single Inheritance
â‹ Multilevel Inheritance
âŒ Hierarchical Inheritance
â Multiple Inheritance
â Hybrid Inheritance
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Inheritance Types Supported by Java
ava SUPPORTS (with classes):
â¡ï¸ Single Inheritance
â¡ï¸ Multilevel Inheritance
â¡ï¸ Hierarchical Inheritance
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Java does NOT support (with classes):
â¡ï¸ Multiple Inheritance
â¡ï¸ Hybrid Inheritance
However, Multiple and Hybrid inheritance ARE supported in Java using interfaces.
â­ï¸  Reason Why Java Does NOT Support Multiple & Hybrid Inheritance (Using Classes)
1. Diamond Problem (Main Reason)
Java does not support multiple inheritance with classes to avoid ambiguity, known as the Diamond Problem.
Example (Problem Scenario):
class A {
    void show() {
        System.out.println("Class A");
    }
}
class B extends A {
}

class C extends A {
}
//  Not allowed in Java
class D extends B, C {
}

Question:
If D calls show(),
which version should be executed?
â–ªï¸ From B (via A)?
â–ªï¸ From C (via A)?
This creates confusion for the compiler.

2. Method Ambiguity
â¡ï¸ When two parent classes have the same method, the child class does not know which method to inherit
â¡ï¸ This leads to compile-time ambiguity
â¡ï¸ Java avoids this situation completely by not allowing multiple inheritance with classes
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
âŠ Single Inheritance (SUPPORTED)
Definition:
â†ªï¸One child class inherits from one parent class.
Structure:
Parent
  â†“
Child
Example:-
class vehicle{
void run(){
System.out.println("Vehicle is Start");
} }
class Bike extends vehicle(){
void speed{
System.out println("Bike are Stop");
} }
public class SingleInheritanceDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Bike b = new Bike();
        b.run();    
        b.speed();   
    }
}

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
â‹ Multilevel Inheritance (SUPPORTED)
Definition:
â†ªï¸A class is derived from another class, which itself is derived from another class.
Structure:
Grandparent
     â†“
Parent
     â†“
Child
Example:-
class Animal {
    void eat() {
        System.out.println("Animal is eating");
    }
}
class Dog extends Animal {
    void bark() {
        System.out.println("Dog is barking");
    }
}
class Puppy extends Dog {
    void weep() {
        System.out.println("Puppy is weeping");
    }
}
public class MultilevelInheritanceDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Puppy p = new Puppy();
        p.eat();   // from Animal
        p.bark();  // from Dog
        p.weep();  // from Puppy
    }
}
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
âŒ Hierarchical Inheritance (SUPPORTED)
Definition:
â†ªï¸Multiple child classes inherit from one single parent class.
Structure:
        Parent
       /      \
   Child1   Child2
Example:-
class Shape {
    void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing shape");
    }
}
class Circle extends Shape {
void area() {
        System.out.println("Area of circle");
    }
}
class Rectangle extends Shape {
    void area() {
        System.out.println("Area of rectangle");
    }
}
public class HierarchicalInheritanceDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Circle c = new Circle();
        c.draw();
        c.area();

        Rectangle r = new Rectangle();
        r.draw();
        r.area();
    }
}
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
â Multiple Inheritance (NOT SUPPORTED with Classes)
Definition:
â†ªï¸A class inherits from more than one parent class.
Structure:
Parent1   Parent2
     \     /
      Child
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
â Hybrid Inheritance (NOT SUPPORTED with Classes)
Definition:
â†ªï¸Combination of two or more inheritance types (e.g., multilevel + multiple).
Status in Java:
Not supported with classes
 Supported using interfaces
